<td>Zhōng yǒu wén jiě</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <i><b>Liberation Through Hearing During the Intermediate State</b></i> (<a href="/wiki/Tibetan_language" title="Tibetan language" class="mw-redirect">Tibetan</a>: <i>bardo</i> "<a href="/wiki/Liminality" title="Liminality">liminality</a>"; <i>thodol</i> as "liberation"<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>), sometimes translated as <b>Liberation Through Hearing</b> or <b>Bardo Thodol</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Funerary_text" title="Funerary text">funerary text</a>. It is often referred to in the West by the more casual title, "<b>Tibetan Book of the Dead</b>", a name which draws a parallel with the ancient Egyptian <a href="/wiki/Book_of_the_Dead" title="Book of the Dead">Book of the Dead</a>, another funerary text.</p>
<p>The Tibetan text describes, and is intended to guide one through, the experiences that the consciousness has after death, during the interval between death and the next <a href="/wiki/Rebirth_(Buddhist)" title="Rebirth (Buddhist)" class="mw-redirect">rebirth</a>. This interval is known in Tibetan as the <a href="/wiki/Bardo" title="Bardo">bardo</a>. The text also includes chapters on the <a href="/wiki/Signs_of_death" title="Signs of death" class="mw-redirect">signs of death</a>, and rituals to undertake when death is closing in, or has taken place. It is the most internationally famous and widespread work of <a href="/wiki/Tibet" title="Tibet">Tibetan</a> <a href="/wiki/Nyingma" title="Nyingma">Nyingma</a> literature.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
